# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: virtual-screening
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] A **chemical library** or compound library is a collection of stored chemicals usually used ultimately in high-throughput screening or industrial manufacture.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] The chemical library can consist in simple terms of a series of stored chemicals.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Each chemical has associated information stored in some kind of database with information such as the chemical structure, purity, quantity, and physiochemical characteristics of the compound.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] In drug discovery high-throughput screening, it is desirable to screen a drug target against a selection of chemicals that try to take advantage of as much of the appropriate chemical space as possible.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] The chemical space of all possible chemical structures is extraordinarily large.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Most stored chemical libraries do not typically have a fully represented or sampled chemical space mostly because of storage and cost concerns.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] An example of a chemical library in drug discovery would be a series of chemicals known to inhibit kinases, or in industrial processes, a series of catalysts known to polymerize resins.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Chemical libraries are usually generated for a specific goal and larger chemical libraries could be made of several groups of smaller libraries stored in the same location.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] In the drug discovery process for instance, a wide range of organic chemicals are needed to test against models of disease in high-throughput screening.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Therefore, most of the chemical synthesis needed to generate chemical libraries in drug discovery is based on organic chemistry.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] A company that is interested in screening for kinase inhibitors in cancer may limit their chemical libraries and synthesis to just those types of chemicals known to have affinity for ATP binding sites or allosteric sites.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Generally, however, most chemical libraries focus on large groups of varied organic chemical series where an organic chemist can make many variations on the same molecular scaffold or molecular backbone.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Sometimes chemicals can be purchased from outside vendors as well and included into an internal chemical library.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Depending upon their scope and design, chemical libraries can also be classified as diverse oriented, Drug-like, Lead-like, peptide-mimetic, Natural Product-like, Targeted against a specific family of biological targets such Kinases, GPCRs, Proteases, PPI etc.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] These chemical libraries are often used in target based drug discovery (reverse pharmacology).
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Among the compound libraries should be annotated the Fragment Compound Libraries, which are mainly used for Fragment-based lead discovery.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Chemical libraries are usually designed by chemists and chemoinformatics scientists and synthesized by organic chemistry and medicinal chemistry.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] The method of chemical library generation usually depends on the project and there are many factors to consider when using rational methods to select screening compounds.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Typically, a range of chemicals is screened against a particular drug target or disease model, and the preliminary "hits", or chemicals that show the desired activity, are re-screened to verify their activity.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Once they are qualified as a "hit" by their repeatability and activity, these particular chemicals are registered and analysed.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Chemoproteomics is a field of study that incorporates the use of chemical libraries to identify protein targets.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Commonalities among the different chemical groups are studied as they are often reflective of a particular chemical subspace.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Additional chemistry work may be needed to further optimize the chemical library in the active portion of the subspace.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] When it is needed, more synthesis is completed to extend out the chemical library in that particular subspace by generating more compounds that are very similar to the original hits.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] This new selection of compounds within this narrow range are further screened and then taken on to more sophisticated models for further validation in the Drug Discovery Hit to Lead process.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] The "chemical space" of all possible organic chemicals is large and increases exponentially with the size of the molecule.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Most chemical libraries do not typically have a fully represented chemical space mostly because of storage and cost concerns.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Because of the expense and effort involved in chemical synthesis, the chemicals must be correctly stored and banked away for later use to prevent early degradation.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Each chemical has a particular shelf life and storage requirement and in a good-sized chemical library, there is a timetable by which library chemicals are disposed of and replaced on a regular basis.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Some chemicals are fairly unstable, radioactive, volatile or flammable and must be stored under careful conditions in accordance with safety standards such as OSHA.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Most chemical libraries are managed with information technologies such as barcoding and relational databases.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Additionally, robotics are necessary to fetch compounds in larger chemical libraries.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Because a chemical library's individual entries can easily reach up into the millions of compounds, the management of even modest-sized chemical libraries can be a full-time endeavor.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-library] Compound management is one such field that attempts to manage and upkeep these chemical libraries as well as maximizing safety and effectiveness in their management.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] A chemical space often referred to in cheminformatics is that of potential pharmacologically active molecules.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] Its size is estimated to be in the order of 1060 molecules.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] There are no rigorous methods for determining the precise size of this space.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] The assumptions used for estimating the number of potential pharmacologically active molecules, however, use the Lipinski rules, in particular the molecular weight limit of 500.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] The estimate also restricts the chemical elements used to be Carbon, Hydrogen, Oxygen, Nitrogen and Sulfur.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] It further makes the assumption of a maximum of 30 atoms to stay below 500 daltons, allows for branching and a maximum of 4 rings and arrives at an estimate of 1063.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] This number is often misquoted in subsequent publications to be the estimated size of the whole organic chemistry space, which would be much larger if including the halogens and other elements.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] In addition to the drug-like space and lead-like space that are, in part, defined by the Lipinski's rule of five, the concept of known drug space (KDS), which is defined by the molecular descriptors of marketed drugs, has also been introduced.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] KDS can be used to help predict the boundaries of chemical spaces for drug development by comparing the structure of the molecules that are undergoing design and synthesis to the molecular descriptor parameters that are defined by the KDS.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] As of October 2024, 219 million molecules were assigned with a Chemical Abstracts Service (CAS) Registry Number.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] ChEMBL Database version 33 record biological activities for 2,431,025 distinct molecules.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] Chemical libraries used for laboratory-based screening for compounds with desired properties are examples for real-world chemical libraries of small size (a few hundred to hundreds of thousands of molecules).
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] Systematic exploration of chemical space is possible by creating *in silico* databases of virtual molecules, which can be visualized by projecting multidimensional property space of molecules in lower dimensions.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] Generation of chemical spaces may involve creating stoichiometric combinations of electrons and atomic nuclei to yield all possible topology isomers for the given construction principles.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] In Cheminformatics, software programs called Structure Generators are used to generate the set of all chemical structure adhering to given boundary conditions.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] Constitutional Isomer Generators, for example, can generate all possible constitutional isomers of a given molecular gross formula.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] In the real world, chemical reactions allow us to move in chemical space.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] The mapping between chemical space and molecular properties is often not unique, meaning that there can be very different molecules exhibiting very similar properties.
[src:virtual-screening/chemical-space] Materials design and drug discovery both involve the exploration of chemical space.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] Cheminformatics has been an active field in various guises since the 1970s and earlier, with activity in academic departments and commercial pharmaceutical research and development departments.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] The term chemoinformatics was defined in its application to drug discovery by F.K.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] Since then, both terms, cheminformatics and chemoinformatics, have been used, although, lexicographically, cheminformatics appears to be more frequently used, despite academics in Europe declaring for the variant chemoinformatics in 2006.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] In 2009, a prominent Springer journal in the field was founded by transatlantic executive editors named the Journal of Cheminformatics.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] Cheminformatics combines the scientific working fields of chemistry, computer science, and information science—for example in the areas of topology, chemical graph theory, information retrieval and data mining in the chemical space.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] Cheminformatics can also be applied to data analysis for various industries like paper and pulp, dyes and such allied industries.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] A primary application of cheminformatics is the storage, indexing, and search of information relating to chemical compounds.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] The efficient search of such stored information includes topics that are dealt with in computer science, such as data mining, information retrieval, information extraction, and machine learning.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] The *in silico* representation of chemical structures uses specialized formats such as the Simplified molecular input line entry specifications (SMILES) or the XML-based Chemical Markup Language.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] These representations are often used for storage in large chemical databases.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] While some formats are suited for visual representations in two- or three-dimensions, others are more suited for studying physical interactions, modeling and docking studies.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] Chemical data can pertain to real or virtual molecules.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] Virtual libraries of compounds may be generated in various ways to explore chemical space and hypothesize novel compounds with desired properties.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] Virtual libraries of classes of compounds (drugs, natural products, diversity-oriented synthetic products) were recently generated using the FOG (fragment optimized growth) algorithm.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] This was done by using cheminformatic tools to train transition probabilities of a Markov chain on authentic classes of compounds, and then using the Markov chain to generate novel compounds that were similar to the training database.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] In contrast to high-throughput screening, virtual screening involves computationally screening *in silico* libraries of compounds, by means of various methods such as docking, to identify members likely to possess desired properties such as biological activity against a given target.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] In some cases, combinatorial chemistry is used in the development of the library to increase the efficiency in mining the chemical space.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] More commonly, a diverse library of small molecules or natural products is screened.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] This is the calculation of quantitative structure–activity relationship and quantitative structure property relationship values, used to predict the activity of compounds from their structures.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] In this context there is also a strong relationship to chemometrics.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] Chemical expert systems are also relevant, since they represent parts of chemical knowledge as an *in silico* representation.
[src:virtual-screening/cheminformatics] There is a relatively new concept of matched molecular pair analysis or prediction-driven MMPA which is coupled with QSAR model in order to identify activity cliff.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] The notion of *chemical similarity* (or *molecular similarity*) is one of the most important concepts in cheminformatics.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] These studies are based on the similar property principle of Johnson and Maggiora, which states: *similar compounds have similar properties*.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] Chemical similarity is often described as an inverse of a measure of distance in descriptor space.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] Examples for inverse distance measures are molecule kernels (graph kernel applied to the description of a molecule as an atom-connectivity graph), that measure the structural similarity of chemical compounds.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] The similarity-based virtual screening (a kind of ligand-based virtual screening) assumes that all compounds in a database that are similar to a query compound have similar biological activity.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] Although this hypothesis is not always valid, quite often the set of retrieved compounds is considerably enriched with actives.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] To achieve high efficacy of similarity-based screening of databases containing millions of compounds, molecular structures are usually represented by *molecular screens* (structural keys) or by fixed-size or variable-size *molecular fingerprints*.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] Molecular screens and fingerprints can contain both 2D- and 3D-information.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] However, the 2D-fingerprints, which are a kind of binary fragment descriptors, dominate in this area.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] Fragment-based structural keys, like MDL keys, are sufficiently good for handling small and medium-sized chemical databases, whereas processing of large databases is performed with fingerprints having much higher information density.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] Fragment-based Daylight, BCI, and UNITY 2D (Tripos) fingerprints are the best known examples.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] The most popular similarity measure for comparing chemical structures represented by means of fingerprints is the Tanimoto (or Jaccard) coefficient *T*.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] Two structures are usually considered similar if *T* > 0.85 (for Daylight fingerprints).
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] However, it is a common misunderstanding that a similarity of *T* > 0.85 reflects similar bioactivities in general ("the 0.85 myth").
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] The concept of chemical similarity can be expanded to consider chemical similarity network theory, where descriptive network properties and graph theory can be applied to analyze large chemical space, estimate chemical diversity and predict drug target.
[src:virtual-screening/molecular-similarity] Recently, 3D chemical similarity networks based on 3D ligand conformation have also been developed, which can be used to identify scaffold hopping ligands.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In medicine, **screening** is a strategy used to look for as-yet-unrecognised conditions or risk markers.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] This testing can be applied to individuals or to a whole population without symptoms or signs of the disease being screened.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Screening interventions are designed to identify conditions which could at some future point turn into disease, thus enabling earlier intervention and management in the hope to reduce mortality and suffering from a disease.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Although screening may lead to an earlier diagnosis, not all screening tests have been shown to benefit the person being screened- overdiagnosis, misdiagnosis, and creating a false sense of security are some potential adverse effects of screening.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Additionally, some screening tests can be inappropriately overused.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] For these reasons, a test used in a screening program, especially for a disease with low incidence, must have good sensitivity in addition to acceptable specificity.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Several types of screening exist: **universal (population-based) screening** involves testing of all individuals in a certain category (for example, all children of a certain age).
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] **Case finding** involves testing a smaller group of people based on the presence of risk factors (for example, because a family member has been diagnosed with a hereditary disease).
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] When delivered to large numbers of people at the population level rather than by individual clinicians, testing asymptomatic people for disease because they have one or more risk factors is sometimes referred to as **targeted** or **stratified screening**.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Screening interventions are not designed to be diagnostic, and often have significant rates of both false positive and false negative results.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In the US, frequently updated recommendations for screening are provided by the independent panel of experts, the United States Preventive Services Task Force.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In the UK, recommendations are provided by the UK National Screening Committee.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In 1968, the World Health Organization published guidelines on the *Principles and practice of screening for disease*, which is often referred to as the *Wilson and Jungner criteria*.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] There should be a treatment for the condition.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Facilities for diagnosis and treatment should be available.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] There should be a latent stage of the disease.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] There should be a test or examination for the condition.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The test should be acceptable to the population.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The natural history of the disease should be adequately understood.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] There should be an agreed policy on whom to treat.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The total cost of finding a case should be economically balanced in relation to medical expenditure as a whole.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Case-finding should be a continuous process, not just a "once and for all" project.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In many countries there are population-based screening programmes.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In some countries, such as the UK, policy is made nationally and programmes are delivered nationwide to uniform quality standards.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Most public school systems in the United States screen students periodically for hearing and vision deficiencies and dental problems.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Screening for spinal and posture issues such as scoliosis is sometimes carried out, but is controversial as scoliosis (unlike vision or dental issues) is found in only a very small segment of the general population and because students must remove their shirts for screening.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Many states no longer mandate scoliosis screenings, or allow them to be waived with parental notification.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] There are currently bills being introduced in various U.S. states to mandate mental health screenings for students attending public schools in hopes to prevent self-harm as well as the harming of peers.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Those proposing these bills hope to diagnose and treat mental illnesses such as depression and anxiety.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The social determinants of health are the economic and social conditions that influence individual and group differences in health status.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Those conditions may have adverse effects on their health and well-being.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] To mitigate those adverse effects, certain health policies like the United States Affordable Care Act (2010) gave increased traction to preventive programs, such as those that routinely screen for social determinants of health.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Screening is believed to a valuable tool in identifying patients' basic needs in a social determinants of health framework so that they can be better served.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] When established in the United States, the Affordable Care Act was able to bridge the gap between community-based health and healthcare as a medical treatment, leading to programs that screened for social determinants of health.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Social determinants of health include social status, gender, ethnicity, economic status, education level, access to services, education, immigrant status, upbringing, and much, much more.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Several clinics across the United States have employed a system in which they screen patients for certain risk factors related to social determinants of health.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In such cases, it is done as a preventive measure in order to mitigate any detrimental effects of prolonged exposure to certain risk factors, or to simply begin remedying the adverse effects already faced by certain individuals.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] They can be structured in different ways, for example, online or in person, and yield different outcomes based on the patient's responses.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Some programs, like the FIND Desk at UCSF Benioff Children's Hospital, employ screening for social determinants of health in order to connect their patients with social services and community resources that may provide patients greater autonomy and mobility.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Medical screening equipment must be capable of fast processing of many cases, but may not need to be as precise as diagnostic equipment.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Screening can detect medical conditions at an early stage before symptoms present while treatment is more effective than for later detection.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Like any medical test, the tests used in screening are not perfect.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The test result may incorrectly show positive for those without disease (false positive), or negative for people who have the condition (false negative).
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Screening for dementia in the English NHS is controversial because it could cause undue anxiety in patients and support services would be stretched.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] To many people, screening instinctively seems like an appropriate thing to do, because catching something earlier seems better.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] There will always be the problems with incorrect results and other issues listed above.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] It is an ethical requirement for balanced and accurate information to be given to participants at the point when screening is offered, in order that they can make a fully informed choice about whether or not to accept.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Before a screening program is implemented, it should be looked at to ensure that putting it in place would do more good than harm.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] A number of different biases, inherent in the study method, will skew results.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Screening may identify abnormalities that would never cause a problem in a person's lifetime.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] An example of this is prostate cancer screening; it has been said that "more men die with prostate cancer than of it".
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Autopsy studies have shown that between 14 and 77% of elderly men who have died of other causes are found to have had prostate cancer.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Aside from issues with unnecessary treatment (prostate cancer treatment is by no means without risk), overdiagnosis makes a study look good at picking up abnormalities, even though they are sometimes harmless.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Overdiagnosis occurs when all of these people with harmless abnormalities are counted as "lives saved" by the screening, rather than as "healthy people needlessly harmed by overdiagnosis".
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] So it might lead to an endless cycle: the greater the overdiagnosis, the more people will think screening is more effective than it is, which can reinforce people to do more screening tests, leading to even more overdiagnosis.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The screening for neuroblastoma, the most common malignant solid tumor in children, in Japan is a very good example of why a screening program must be evaluated rigorously before it is implemented.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In 1981, Japan started a program of screening for neuroblastoma by measuring homovanillic acid and vanilmandelic acid in urine samples of six-month-old infants.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In 2003, a special committee was organized to evaluate the motivation for the neuroblastoma screening program.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In the same year, the committee concluded that there was sufficient evidence that screening method used in the time led to overdiagnosis, but there was no enough evidence that the program reduced neuroblastoma deaths.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] As such, the committee recommended against screening and the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare decided to stop the screening program.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Another example of overdiagnosis happened with thyroid cancer: its incidence tripled in United States between 1975 and 2009, while mortality was constant.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In South Korea, the situation was even worse with 15-fold increase in the incidence from 1993 to 2011 (the world's greatest increase of thyroid cancer incidence), while the mortality remained stable.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The increase in incidence was associated with the introduction of ultrasonography screening.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The problem of overdiagnosis in cancer screening is that at the time of diagnosis it not possible to differentiate between a harmless lesion and lethal one, unless the patient is not treated and dies from other causes.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] So almost all patients tend to be treated, leading to what is called overtreatment.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] If screening works, it must diagnose the target disease earlier than it would be without screening (when symptoms appear).
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Even if in both cases (with screening vs without screening) patients die at the same time, just because the disease was diagnosed earlier by screening, the *survival time since diagnosis* is longer in screened people than in persons who was not screened.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] This happens even when *life span* has not been prolonged.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] As the diagnosis was made earlier without life being prolonged, the patient might be more anxious as he must live with knowledge of his diagnosis for longer.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] If screening works, it must introduce a *lead time*.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] So statistics of survival time since diagnosis tends to increase with screening because of the lead time introduced, even when screening offers no benefits.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] If we do not think about what *survival time* actually means in this context, we might attribute success to a screening test that does nothing but advance diagnosis.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] As survival statistics suffers from this and other biases, comparing the disease mortality (or even all-cause mortality) between screened and unscreened population gives more meaningful information.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Many screening tests involve the detection of cancers.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Screening is more likely to detect slower-growing tumors (due to longer pre-clinical sojourn time) that are less likely to cause harm.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Also, those aggressive cancers tend to produce symptoms in the gap between scheduled screening, being less likely to be detected by screening.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] So, the cases screening often detects automatically have better prognosis than symptomatic cases.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The consequence is those more slow progressive cases are now classified as cancers, which increases the incidence, and due to its better prognosis, the survival rates of screened people will be better than non-screened people even if screening makes no difference.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Not everyone will partake in a screening program.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] There are factors that differ between those willing to get tested and those who are not.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Selection bias may also make a test look better than it really is.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] If a test is more available to young and healthy people (for instance if people have to travel a long distance to get checked) then fewer people in the screening population will have negative outcomes than for a random sample, and the test will seem to make a positive difference.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Studies have shown that people who attend screening tend to be healthier than those who do not.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] This has been called the healthy screenee effect, which is a form of selection bias.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The reason seems to be that people who are healthy, affluent, physically fit, non-smokers with long-lived parents are more likely to come and get screened than those on low-income, who have existing health and social problems.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] One example of selection bias occurred in Edinbourg trial of mammography screening, which used cluster randomisation.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The trial found reduced cardiovascular mortality in those who were screened for breast cancer.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] That happened because baseline differences regarding socio-economic status in the groups: 26% of the women in the control group and 53% in the study group belonged to the highest socioeconomic level.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Cardiovascular risk screening is a vital tool in reducing the global incidence of cardiovascular diseases.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The best way to minimize selection bias is to use a randomized controlled trial, though observational, naturalistic, or retrospective studies can be of some value and are typically easier to conduct.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Any study must be sufficiently large (include many patients) and sufficiently long (follow patients for many years) to have the statistical power to assess the true value of a screening program.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] For rare diseases, hundreds of thousands of patients may be needed to realize the value of screening (find enough treatable disease), and to assess the effect of the screening program on mortality a study may have to follow the cohort for decades.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] Such studies take a long time and are expensive, but can provide the most useful data with which to evaluate the screening program and practice evidence-based medicine.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The main outcome of cancer screening studies is usually the number of deaths caused by the disease being screened for - this is called disease-specific mortality.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] To give an example: in trials of mammography screening for breast cancer, the main outcome reported is often breast cancer mortality.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] However, disease-specific mortality might be biased in favor of screening.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In the example of breast cancer screening, women overdiagnosed with breast cancer might receive radiotherapy, which increases mortality due to lung cancer and heart disease.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The problem is those deaths are often classified as other causes and might even be larger than the number of breast cancer deaths avoided by screening.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] So the non-biased outcome is all-cause mortality.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] The problem is that much larger trials are needed to detect a significant reduction in all-cause mortality.
[src:virtual-screening/screening-medicine] In 2016, researcher Vinay Prasad and colleagues published an article in *BMJ* titled "Why cancer screening has never been shown to save lives", as cancer screening trials did not show all-cause mortality reduction.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Virtual screening has been defined as "automatically evaluating very large libraries of compounds" using computer programs.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] As this definition suggests, VS has largely been a numbers game focusing on how the enormous chemical space of over 1060 conceivable compounds can be filtered to a manageable number that can be synthesized, purchased, and tested.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Although searching the entire chemical universe may be a theoretically interesting problem, more practical VS scenarios focus on designing and optimizing targeted combinatorial libraries and enriching libraries of available compounds from in-house compound repositories or vendor offerings.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] As the accuracy of the method has increased, virtual screening has become an integral part of the drug discovery process.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Virtual Screening can be used to select in house database compounds for screening, choose compounds that can be purchased externally, and to choose which compound should be synthesized next.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] There are two broad categories of screening techniques: ligand-based and structure-based.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Given a set of structurally diverse ligands that binds to a receptor, a model of the receptor can be built by exploiting the collective information contained in such set of ligands.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Different computational techniques explore the structural, electronic, molecular shape, and physicochemical similarities of different ligands that could imply their mode of action against a specific molecular receptor or cell lines.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] A candidate ligand can then be compared to the pharmacophore model to determine whether it is compatible with it and therefore likely to bind.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Different 2D chemical similarity analysis methods have been used to scan a databases to find active ligands.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Another popular approach used in ligand-based virtual screening consist on searching molecules with shape similar to that of known actives, as such molecules will fit the target's binding site and hence will be likely to bind the target.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] There are a number of prospective applications of this class of techniques in the literature.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Pharmacophoric extensions of these 3D methods are also freely-available as webservers.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Also shape based virtual screening has gained significant popularity.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Structure-based virtual screening approach includes different computational techniques that consider the structure of the receptor that is the molecular target of the investigated active ligands.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Some of these techniques include molecular docking, structure-based pharmacophore modelling, and molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Molecular docking is the most used structure-based technique, and it applies a scoring function to estimate the fitness of each ligand against the binding site of the macromolecular receptor, helping to choose the ligands with the most high affinity.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Currently, there are some webservers oriented to prospective virtual screening.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Hybrid methods that rely on structural and ligand similarity were also developed to overcome the limitations of traditional VLS approaches.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] This methodologies utilizes evolution‐based ligand‐binding information to predict small-molecule binders and can employ both global structural similarity and pocket similarity.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] A global structural similarity based approach employs both an experimental structure or a predicted protein model to find structural similarity with proteins in the PDB holo‐template library.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Upon detecting significant structural similarity, 2D fingerprint based Tanimoto coefficient metric is applied to screen for small-molecules that are similar to ligands extracted from selected holo PDB templates.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The predictions from this method have been experimentally assessed and shows good enrichment in identifying active small molecules.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The above specified method depends on global structural similarity and is not capable of *a priori* selecting a particular ligand‐binding site in the protein of interest.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Further, since the methods rely on 2D similarity assessment for ligands, they are not capable of recognizing stereochemical similarity of small-molecules that are substantially different but demonstrate geometric shape similarity.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] To address these concerns, a new pocket centric approach, *PoLi,* capable of targeting specific binding pockets in holo‐protein templates, was developed and experimentally assessed.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The computation of pair-wise interactions between atoms, which is a prerequisite for the operation of many virtual screening programs, scales by $O(N^{2})$ , *N* is the number of atoms in the system.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Due to the quadratic scaling, the computational costs increase quickly.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Ligand-based methods typically require a fraction of a second for a single structure comparison operation.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Sometimes a single CPU is enough to perform a large screening within hours.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] However, several comparisons can be made in parallel in order to expedite the processing of a large database of compounds.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The size of the task requires a parallel computing infrastructure, such as a cluster of Linux systems, running a batch queue processor to handle the work, such as Sun Grid Engine or Torque PBS.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] A means of handling the input from large compound libraries is needed.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] This requires a form of compound database that can be queried by the parallel cluster, delivering compounds in parallel to the various compute nodes.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Commercial database engines may be too ponderous, and a high speed indexing engine, such as Berkeley DB, may be a better choice.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Furthermore, it may not be efficient to run one comparison per job, because the ramp up time of the cluster nodes could easily outstrip the amount of useful work.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] To work around this, it is necessary to process batches of compounds in each cluster job, aggregating the results into some kind of log file.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] A secondary process, to mine the log files and extract high scoring candidates, can then be run after the whole experiment has been run.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The aim of virtual screening is to identify molecules of novel chemical structure that bind to the macromolecular target of interest.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Thus, success of a virtual screen is defined in terms of finding interesting new scaffolds rather than the total number of hits.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Interpretations of virtual screening accuracy should, therefore, be considered with caution.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Low hit rates of interesting scaffolds are clearly preferable over high hit rates of already known scaffolds.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Most tests of virtual screening studies in the literature are retrospective.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] In these studies, the performance of a VS technique is measured by its ability to retrieve a small set of previously known molecules with affinity to the target of interest (active molecules or just actives) from a library containing a much higher proportion of assumed inactives or decoys.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] There are several distinct ways to select decoys by matching the properties of the corresponding active molecule and more recently decoys are also selected in a property-unmatched manner.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The actual impact of decoy selection, either for training or testing purposes, has also been discussed.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] By contrast, in prospective applications of virtual screening, the resulting hits are subjected to experimental confirmation (e.g., IC50 measurements).
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] There is consensus that retrospective benchmarks are not good predictors of prospective performance and consequently only prospective studies constitute conclusive proof of the suitability of a technique for a particular target.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Virtual screening is a very useful application when it comes to identifying hit molecules as a beginning for medicinal chemistry.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] As the virtual screening approach begins to become a more vital and substantial technique within the medicinal chemistry industry the approach has had an expeditious increase.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Ligand-based methods are applied when the three-dimensional structure of the target receptor is unknown.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Instead of modeling ligand–receptor interactions directly, these approaches rely on the structural and physicochemical properties of known active ligands to predict how new compounds may bind.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] A **pharmacophore** is defined as the ensemble of steric and electronic features necessary to ensure optimal supramolecular interactions with a biological target and to trigger (or block) its biological response.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] These features typically include hydrogen-bond donors and acceptors, hydrophobic regions, aromatic rings, charged groups, and metal-binding functionalities.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Pharmacophore modeling is commonly applied in ligand-based drug design when the three-dimensional structure of the target protein is unknown or when multiple active ligands are available.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] **Conformer generation:** Because ligands are flexible, multiple low-energy conformations (conformers) are generated for each molecule.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] This step aims to approximate the bioactive conformation, which is usually unknown in ligand-based approaches.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] **Molecular alignment and superposition:** The generated conformers are superimposed to identify common spatial arrangements of key chemical features.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] By aligning shared pharmacophoric elements across active ligands, a pharmacophore hypothesis is constructed.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Unlike approaches that rely on a single reference structure, pharmacophore modeling integrates information from multiple active compounds.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] This generally improves robustness and predictive performance, particularly when dealing with chemically diverse ligands.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] However, because multiple alignments and feature combinations are possible, pharmacophore modeling does not usually yield a single unique solution.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Therefore, generated hypotheses must be validated using external test sets or experimental data.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Shape-based molecular similarity approaches have been established as important and popular virtual screening techniques.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] At present, the highly optimized screening platform ROCS (Rapid Overlay of Chemical Structures) is considered the de facto industry standard for shape-based, ligand-centric virtual screening.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] It uses a Gaussian function to define molecular volumes of small organic molecules.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Other shape-based molecular similarity methods such as Autodock-SS have also been developed.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Field-based virtual screening methods extend shape-based similarity approaches by considering not only molecular shape but also the physicochemical interaction fields that govern ligand–receptor recognition.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] By evaluating these properties in three-dimensional space, field-based approaches aim to capture the underlying interaction patterns responsible for biological activity, while remaining largely independent of the specific chemical scaffold of the query molecule.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Compared to purely shape-based methods, field-based screening can provide a more nuanced description of molecular similarity, particularly when structurally distinct compounds share similar interaction profiles.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Quantitative Structure–Activity Relationship (QSAR) models are predictive models that relate molecular descriptors to biological activity using a dataset of known active and inactive compounds.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] In contrast to qualitative structure–activity relationship (SAR) analysis, which identifies trends within structural classes, QSAR provides a quantitative mathematical relationship between molecular properties and measured biological responses.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] These methods assume a linear relationship between descriptors and biological activity.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] QSAR models are widely used to prioritize compounds in lead discovery and optimization.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Machine learning (ML) approaches can be viewed as an extension of QSAR methodology.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Like classical QSAR models, ML-based methods use molecular descriptors or structural representations (such as molecular fingerprint, graphs) as input features.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] However, they employ more flexible algorithms capable of modeling nonlinear and complex relationships between molecular structure and biological activity.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] In supervised learning, models are trained on datasets composed of known active and inactive compounds (or compounds with measured activity values).
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The trained model is then used to predict the activity or probability of activity for new compounds.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Structure-based methods rely on the three-dimensional structure of the biological target, typically obtained from X-ray crystallography, NMR spectroscopy, or cryo-electron microscopy.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Unlike ligand-based approaches, these methods explicitly model the interactions between a ligand and the binding site of a receptor.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] In structure-based pharmacophore modeling, pharmacophoric features are derived directly from the three-dimensional structure of the target binding site, rather than from a set of known active ligands.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Key interaction features - such as hydrogen-bond donors and acceptors, hydrophobic regions, charged residues, and metal-binding sites - are identified based on the spatial arrangement of amino acid residues within the binding pocket.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] If a protein–ligand complex structure is available, pharmacophoric features can also be extracted from the observed ligand–receptor interactions.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The resulting pharmacophore model represents the essential interaction pattern required for binding and can be used to screen compound libraries.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Molecular docking aims to predict the binding mode (pose) and, in some cases, the binding affinity of a ligand within the active site of a target protein.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] **Scoring function** – estimates the strength of the ligand–receptor interaction and ranks predicted poses accordingly.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] The goal is to identify the most probable binding pose for a given ligand and to prioritize compounds based on their predicted binding affinity.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Co-folding methods predict the structure of a protein–ligand complex by modeling the receptor and ligand simultaneously, allowing conformational adaptation during binding.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Unlike classical docking, which typically treats the receptor as rigid or semi-flexible, co-folding approaches aim to capture induced-fit effects more explicitly.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Recent deep learning–based frameworks such as **Boltz-2** exemplify this strategy by predicting bound complex structures directly from sequence and ligand information.
[src:virtual-screening/virtual-screening] Although such approaches are computationally more demanding than traditional docking, they hold promise for refining binding poses, improving structural accuracy, and enhancing structure-based virtual screening workflows, particularly for flexible or challenging targets.
